1	#pragma once
2	/*
3	 * Data types describing the physical components on the FPGA architecture.
4	 *
5	 * We assume an island style FPGA where complex logic blocks are arranged in a grid and each side of the logic block has access to the inter-block interconnect.  To keep the logic blocks general,
6	 * we allow arbitrary hierarchy, modes, primitives, and interconnect within each complex logic block.  The data structures here describe the properties of the island-style FPGA as well as the details on
7	 * hierarchy, modes, primitives, and interconnects within each logic block.
8	 *
9	 * Data structures that flesh out
10	 *
11	 * The data structures that store the
12	 *
13	 * Key data types:
14	 * t_physical_tile_type: represents the type of a tile in the device grid and describes its physical characteristics (pin locations, area, width, height, etc.)
15	 * t_logical_block_type: represents and describes the type of a clustered block
16	 * pb_type: describes the types of physical blocks within the t_logical_block_type in a hierarchy where the top block is the complex block and the leaf blocks implement one logical block
17	 * pb_graph_node: is a flattened version of pb_type so a pb_type with 10 instances will have 10 pb_graph_nodes representing each instance
18	 *
19	 * Additional notes:
20	 *
21	 * The interconnect specified in the architecture file gets flattened out in the pb_graph_node netlist.  Each pb_graph_node contains pb_graph_pins which allow it to connect to other pb_graph_nodes.
22	 * These pins are in connected to other pins through pb_graph_edges. The pin connections are based on what is specified in the <interconnect> tags of the architecture file.
23	 *
24	 * Date: February 19, 2009
25	 * Authors: Jason Luu and Kenneth Kent
26	 */
